<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,985,1291]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName box="[396,531,985,1010]" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Longistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[396,531,985,1010]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Longistylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[538,617,985,1011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Main" authorityName="Main" box="[748,865,985,1011]" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Teyl" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[748,793,985,1010]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Teyl</emphasis>
Main
</taxonomicName>
by the very long, styliform embolus of the male palpal bulb, but differs by the reflexed embolus at least twice as long as the palpal tibia (
<figureCitation box="[333,443,1065,1091]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[264,382,1331,1355]" captionTargetBox="[338,1276,436,1310]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[311,1300,423,1324]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Longistylus ygapema n. sp. 1 – 3. Left male palpal bulb. 1, Prolateral view; 2, Dorsal view; 3, Retrolateral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273335/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Figs. 
<number box="[400,443,1065,1091]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName box="[501,546,1065,1090]" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Teyl" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[501,546,1065,1090]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Teyl</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
never longer than tibia), and by the pseudosegmented tarsi (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 18" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,576,1710]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[300,1293,576,1710]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 18. Longistylus ygapema n. sp. 11 – 18. 11, Male sternum, endites and ratellum. 12, Tibia I, retrolateral view; 13, Tarsus IV pseudosgmentation, lateral view; 14, Tarsus IV pseudosegmentation, variation, lateral view; 15, Tarsus IV pseudosegmentation, variation, lateral view; 16, Male palpal bulb, prolateral view; 17, Retrolateral view; 18, Ventral view. Scale bars = 2 mm. Photos: R. P. Indicatti." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273337/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Figs. 
<number box="[264,339,1105,1131]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). It is distinguished from the ramaining Anaminae genera by the triangular apical segment of PLS (
<figureCitation box="[468,538,1145,1171]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 10" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,726,1775]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[300,1293,726,1775]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 10. Longistylus ygapema n. sp. 4 – 10. 4, Male body, dorsal view; 5, Cephalothorax, dorsal view; 6, Abdomen, ventral view; 7, Lateral view; 8, Ventral view; 9, Lateral view, showing color variation; 10, Dorsal view, showing color variation. Scale bars = 2 mm. Photos: R. P. Indicatti." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273336/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[523,538,1145,1171]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
) and by the absence of megaspine on male tibia I and II (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1300,1145,1171]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 18" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,576,1710]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[300,1293,576,1710]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 18. Longistylus ygapema n. sp. 11 – 18. 11, Male sternum, endites and ratellum. 12, Tibia I, retrolateral view; 13, Tarsus IV pseudosgmentation, lateral view; 14, Tarsus IV pseudosegmentation, variation, lateral view; 15, Tarsus IV pseudosegmentation, variation, lateral view; 16, Male palpal bulb, prolateral view; 17, Retrolateral view; 18, Ventral view. Scale bars = 2 mm. Photos: R. P. Indicatti." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273337/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[1267,1300,1145,1171]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,985,1291]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Etymology. The generic name refers to the very long embolus of the male palp (from the Latin: 
<emphasis box="[385,437,1225,1250]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">long</emphasis>
+ 
<emphasis box="[468,535,1225,1250]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">stylus</emphasis>
, pointed tip). Gender is male.
</paragraph>
